posts.com:
Fondé en 2001, LEON est un magazine de mode masculine, dédié auchoiwaruoyaji,que nous pouvons traduire plus ou moins par "the bad-ass middle-aged man".
Avec une cible de lecteurs dans leur trentaine ou quarantaine, disposant de revenus conséquents, ce magazine de niche couvre l'élégance et la sophistication à l'européenne, et plus particulièrement les tendances italiennes.
Girolamo Panzetta, expatrié italien souvent vu à la télévision japonaise, est présent sur presque toutes les couvertures du magazine (il détient d'ailleurs le record du plus grand nombre de couvertures de magazines consécutives).
Présentant un assortiment des plus beaux costumes, chaussures polies, accessoires chics, et même une sous-section sur le sport, LEONprésente tous les essentiels del'homme d'âge moyen moderne qui cherche à resteren phase avec les tendances européennes.

go for anime/movies with subtitles

binge watch for 2 weeks at least 4 hours a day
when you see ANYTHING you don't get, pause and go to:
deepl.com
translate.yandex/google
multitran
wiki cross-references
context-reverso
image with illustrated prepositions/image search

dont watch further unless you get the main point of what was said

after 2 weeks you'd be c2 at the very least
even if you'd only watch basic things like naturo

that's basically the only way to learn to comprehend the language
- cards: don't land you ahead of the Ebbinghaus curve, you also won't learn the communicative speech
- textbooks: same as cards, and cost a fortune, and as for Russian language literature, they only promote talentless frankfurt school kikes
ofc it's a good option to read something you already know
- going to Russia or finding Russian friends: you'd have to be extroverted to do so and learn anything

you can use "most commonly used X*100 words in Russian" lists to track your progress, you'd be amazed how fast you'd go from looking every word in the book to getting first 100, then 300, then 800, then 1500 words

prior to it, you can switch your phone to Russian interface to get accustomed with alphabet and a couple of most common interface words like "search", "bookmarks", "clock", "calc", etc.

Back in the 90 and onward V4 had huge prestige due to their anti-communist resistance. They also could present their regimes as just a foreign occupation and the fall of communism as a liberation.
For us it was an "embarrassment" because Ceausescu was more of a local leader who actually was popular at some point and stood against the Soviets, and we really couldn't present the fall of communism as a "glorious liberation" form a foreign rule.

>寂しさに思い出さえ切なく滲む。
滲む can be both transitive and intransitive. Here this 滲む is used intransitively.
More importantly, one of "Nounに"'s meanings is "due to the Noun/because of the Noun", being used here. Nouns that allow this usage is limited (probably emotional expressions).
e.g. 喜びにとび上がる = to jump with delight
悲しみに何もやる気が出ない = grief takes away all motivation.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>176538241
A basic rule is that は can replace を (as long as readers can recognize that the replaced particle is を).
So in this case は essentially means を with は's own characteristic.
The same is true of が. は replaces が without changing が's original function. In my opinion は vs が argument is meaningless because they live in different spheres.
Other particles are not be completely replaced by but turned into "compound" particles like に -> には but the logic remains the same. には is essentially に but は's nuance is added.

>when a large country legally merges a small country
It's basically the same in english, but I think the word annex gets a negative reputation because of the power imbalance between two countries in that sort of situation, and western culture doesn't like power imbalances like that. It's why the few remaining European colonial territories are typically called "dependencies" and given a large degree of autonomy. It probably doesn't help that schools use the word annex when talking about Hitler taking over Austria.

If there was a case of a small country merging into a large country, It would most likely be said that the small country "joined" the large country" since it puts the lesser partner as the subject, implying that it was a voluntary choice by them.

>>176620217
>since は is used instead of わ as a topic particle, what is わ used for? I dont think i've seen it anywhere so far
わ is just a character, not a particle. A simple word that uses it is 川 (river) which is spelt in hiragana as かわ.

Another place the character わ is used is in the negative conjugations of verbs ending with う. If you've ever seen a japanese verb, you'll notice that they are typically a kanji with a hiragana ending, such as 買う (かう / to buy). The reason verbs end in hiragana is so the verb can be conjugated easily. In the negative form of 買う, the う is replaced with わない, making it 買わない (かわない / to not buy). This process works if you want to convert any verb ending in う into the negative.

Oh, you can also theoretically put わ onto the end of your sentence if you want to sound like a girl I guess. Not really sure what it means or how common it's use is, but it sounds cute.

posts.name: Anonymous

>>176596288
No, this is not what I'm talking about.
The contrast between the sounds "sz" and "ś" is shown not just by the consonants, but also by adjacent vowels.
For example, the vowel sound in "wiesz" is acoustically different than the one in "wieś", because the latter is affected by the following soft consonant. Native speakers subconsciously utilize this to make perception easier.
I remember reading somewhere that for children, it's even the main cue during certain periods of development.

Boys in 9th century Germany

First they would memoirs the Psalms even without understanding what it meant
Then the Distichs of Cato and fables
Now they would get a grammar text by Alcuin, but another by Donatus also was very common
They also parsed lots of Latin as the main part of their learning

So in three years they were expected to be fluent in Latin spoken and read or by the time they were ten.

The Alcuin book was Dialogus Franconis et Saxonis de octo partibus
orationis

The source of the material was Reading in Medieval St. Gall by Grotans
